{"title_page": "Daniel Renoult", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Daniel Renoult 1921.jpg|thumb|right|Renoult in 1921 at the 1st Congress of the Communist Party in [[Marseilles]]]]\n'''Daniel Renoult''' (December 18, 1880 \u2013 July 17, 1958) was a [[French Communist Party]] (''Parti communiste fran\u00e7ais'', PCF) politician, an activist and journalist. He was [[Mayor (France)|Mayor]] of [[Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis|Montreuil]] from 1944 to his death in 1958, during which he made some major changes and contributions to the city.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn December 18, 1880 in the [[5th arrondissement of Paris]], [[France]] into a bourgeois family, Renoult was raised Republican and Progressive.<ref name=\"Houssin2004\">{{cite book|last=Houssin|first=Monique|title=R\u00e9sistantes et r\u00e9sistants en Seine-Saint-Denis: Un nom, une rue, une histoire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VL52RZBV4xUC&pg=PA135|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=2004|publisher=Editions de l'Atelier|isbn=978-2-7082-3730-8|page=135}}</ref> He was the son of a lawyer and the brother of a radical minister in the government, [[Aristide Briand]]. When Renoult was a young student, he was caught in the tide of opinion raised by the defense of Captain Dreyfus.\n\nIn 1906, he helped, with [[Jean Jaur\u00e8s]], [[Jules Guesde]] and [[\u00c9douard Vaillant]], in the development of the [[French Section of the Workers' International]] (''Section Fran\u00e7aise de l'Internationale Ouvri\u00e8re'', SFIO) and in 1908, he joined the newspaper ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'', writing on the topic of parliamentary affairs. He witnessed Jaur\u00e8s assassination on July 31, 1914. He served as an infantry sergeant in the Middle East. After the conflict, he became a [[pacifist]] and resumed his journalistic profession alongside [[Gabriel Peri]]. He was an admirer of the Bolsheviks and events in Russia during this period,<ref name=\"Wohl1966\">{{cite book|last=Wohl|first=Robert|title=French Communism in the Making, 1914-1924|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fZ6aAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA187|accessdate=30 April 2012|date=1 June 1966|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-0177-8|pages=187, 214}}</ref> and was a leader of the [[Comintern]] (\"Third International\").<ref name=\"Chisholm1922\">{{cite book|last=Chisholm|first=Hugh|title=The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica: a dictionary of arts, sciences, literature and general information|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K2oNAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA132|accessdate=1 May 2012|edition=Public domain|year=1922|publisher=At the University press|pages=132\u2013}}</ref>\n\nRenoult and [[G\u00e9rard Longuet]] attended the Comintern's Halle congress in October 1920.<ref name=\"Wolfe1981\">{{cite book|last=Wolfe|first=Bertram David|title=Revolution and reality: essays on the origin and fate of the Soviet system|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iD0FAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=1 May 2012|date=July 1981|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=978-0-8078-1453-6|page=174}}</ref> Two months later, Renoult was one of the delegates at [[French Section of the Workers' International|SFIO]]'s [[Tours Congress]], where he voted for the split that gave rise to the PCF. Described as, \"One of the leading figures of the Reconstructionist Committee\" in March 1920, he traveled to Italy to try to \"dissuade [[Giacinto Menotti Serrati|Serrati]] and the rest of the [[Direzione]] from their earlier refusal to participate in a reconstructionist conference\" but was poorly received by them.<ref name=\"Lindemann1974\">{{cite book|last=Lindemann|first=Albert S.|title=The Red Years: European Socialism Versus Bolshevism, 1919-1921|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zWuUwtSVwRQC&pg=PA111|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=1974|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-02511-0|page=111}}</ref> Renoult attending the 1st Congress of the PCF in [[Marseilles]] in 1921, as did [[Charles Rappoport]], Renoult, [[Ludovic-Oscar Frossard]], and [[Marcel Cachin]]. Renoult was referred to as being one of Cachin's henchman.<ref name=\"ActivitiesLusk1920\">{{cite book|author1=New York (State). Legislature. Joint Legislative Committee to Investigate Seditious Activities|last2=Lusk|first2=Clayton Riley|title=Revolutionary Radicalism: (vol. III-IV) Constructive movements and measures in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GYnaAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1562|accessdate=1 May 2012|edition=Public domain|year=1920|publisher=J. B. Lyon|pages=1562\u2013}}</ref> As a veteran political activist, he arrived in [[Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis|Montreuil]] in 1928.\n[[File:Congr\u00e8s PCF 1921 - Rappoport, Renoult, Frossard, Cachin.jpg|thumb|left|Renoult at the 1st Congress of the PCF in [[Marseilles]] in 1921. From the left, [[Charles Rappoport]], Renoult, [[Ludovic-Oscar Frossard]], and [[Marcel Cachin]].]]\nHe was first elected as the first Communist Deputy on May 19, 1935, then general councillor of the [[Seine]] on May 26 of that year. However, he was suspended on October 5, 1939 pursuant to an order of the [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]], which dissolved all Communist municipal councils of the Seine and the [[Oise]]. On October 26, 1939, the PCF was dissolved and on February 14, 1940, Renoult was arrested in Paris. He was taken to the [[Baillet]] camp, then transferred to the [[Ile d'Yeu]] in April 1940, [[Camp Gurs]], [[Camp Nexon]], citadel of [[Sisteron]], locked in the camp of [[Saint-Sulpice-la-Pointe|Saint-Sulpice]], then moved to the prison at Castres, again to Nexon camp and back to Castres, then again to Saint-Sulpice in prison Eysses, to Camp [[Carri\u00e8re]] and finally in 1944 moved to the citadel of Sisteron again.\n\nOn July 19, 1944, he was released and returned to Montreuil. On September 5 of that year, he was given the presidency of the Local Committee of Liberation and the provisional presidency of the municipality.<ref name=\"Houssin2004\"/> He was elected President of the Union of Mayors of the Seine and Vice President of the [[Association of Mayors of France]] (''Association des maires de France'', AMF). He was re-elected [[Mayor (France)|mayor]] of Montreuil in October 1947 and April 1953, and [[General councils (France)|General Councillor]] in May 1953. Sick at the time of the events of May 1958, he devoted his last energy to the defense of the Republic. Under his leadership, several projects were launched including the development of a site which would become to the [[Parc des Beaumonts]], unemployment assistance, social housing, and the creation of institutions that still exist today. He built health centres, the new library, and the Montreuil Veterans Home amongst others.\n\nRenoult was described as sincere, stormy, and extreme.<ref name=\"Wohl1966\" /> He died July 17, 1958, at his home, 10 Rue Parmentier in Montreuil leaving two messages in advance which gave a lucid sense of his impending doom. One mentioned his attachment to the city of Montreuil, the other to remind people of his loyalty to the French Communist Party and its ideals of youth. However, in a 1953 publication by [[Leon Trotsky]], Trotsky said \"Comrade Daniel Renault, instead of explaining the adopted decisions and instead of calling for their unanimous fulfillment, has engaged in a bitter campaign against the tactic of the united front and against the Communist International as a whole.\"<ref name=\"Trotsky1953\">{{cite book|last=Trotsky|first=Leon|title=The first five years of the Communist International|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zpsgAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=1953|publisher=Pioneer publishers|page=150}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=M6tiQwAACAAJ ''L'Internationale, journal communiste du soir...''] (1921)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Renoult, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:People from Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis]]\n[[Category:French Communist Party politicians]]\n[[Category:French communists]]\n[[Category:French journalists]]\n[[Category:Marxist journalists]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Daniel Renoult 1921.jpg|thumb|right|Renoult in 1921 at the 1st Congress of the Communist Party in [[Marseilles]]]]\n'''Daniel Renoult''' (December 18, 1880 \u2013 July 17, 1958) was a [[French Communist Party]] (''Parti communiste fran\u00e7ais'', PCF) politician, an activist and journalist. He was [[Mayor (France)|Mayor]] of [[Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis|Montreuil]] from 1944 to his death in 1958, during which he made some major changes and contributions to the city.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn December 18, 1880 in the [[5th arrondissement of Paris]], [[France]] into a bourgeois family, Renoult was raised Republican and Progressive.<ref name=\"Houssin2004\">{{cite book|last=Houssin|first=Monique|title=R\u00e9sistantes et r\u00e9sistants en Seine-Saint-Denis: Un nom, une rue, une histoire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VL52RZBV4xUC&pg=PA135|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=2004|publisher=Editions de l'Atelier|isbn=978-2-7082-3730-8|page=135}}</ref> He was the son of a lawyer and the brother of a radical minister in the government, [[Aristide Briand]]. When Renoult was a young student, he was caught in the tide of opinion raised by the defense of Captain Dreyfus.\n\nIn 1906, he helped, with [[Jean Jaur\u00e8s]], [[Jules Guesde]] and [[\u00c9douard Vaillant]], in the development of the [[French Section of the Workers' International]] (''Section Fran\u00e7aise de l'Internationale Ouvri\u00e8re'', SFIO) and in 1908, he joined the newspaper ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'', writing on the topic of parliamentary affairs. He witnessed Jaur\u00e8s assassination on July 31, 1914. He served as an infantry sergeant in the Middle East. After the conflict, he became a [[pacifist]] and resumed his journalistic profession alongside [[Gabriel Peri]]. He was an admirer of the Bolsheviks and events in Russia during this period,<ref name=\"Wohl1966\">{{cite book|last=Wohl|first=Robert|title=French Communism in the Making, 1914-1924|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fZ6aAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA187|accessdate=30 April 2012|date=1 June 1966|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-0177-8|pages=187, 214}}</ref> and was a leader of the [[Comintern]] (\"Third International\").<ref name=\"Chisholm1922\">{{cite book|last=Chisholm|first=Hugh|title=The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica: a dictionary of arts, sciences, literature and general information|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K2oNAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA132|accessdate=1 May 2012|edition=Public domain|year=1922|publisher=At the University press|pages=132\u2013}}</ref>\n\nRenoult and [[G\u00e9rard Longuet]] attended the Comintern's Halle congress in October 1920.<ref name=\"Wolfe1981\">{{cite book|last=Wolfe|first=Bertram David|title=Revolution and reality: essays on the origin and fate of the Soviet system|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iD0FAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=1 May 2012|date=July 1981|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=978-0-8078-1453-6|page=174}}</ref> Two months later, Renoult was one of the delegates at [[French Section of the Workers' International|SFIO]]'s [[Tours Congress]], where he voted for the split that gave rise to the PCF. Described as, \"One of the leading figures of the Reconstructionist Committee\" in March 1920, he traveled to Italy to try to \"dissuade [[Giacinto Menotti Serrati|Serrati]] and the rest of the [[Direzione]] from their earlier refusal to participate in a reconstructionist conference\" but was poorly received by them.<ref name=\"Lindemann1974\">{{cite book|last=Lindemann|first=Albert S.|title=The Red Years: European Socialism Versus Bolshevism, 1919-1921|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zWuU